00:22:54.211 --> 00:22:59.041
Now, as to the legacy of Joan of Arc, she is, as you heard

00:22:59.041 --> 00:23:02.131
at the start of the episode, a patron saint of France.

00:23:02.751 --> 00:23:07.401
She was canonised, turned into a saint, by the pope in 1920.

00:23:08.721 --> 00:23:13.481
And since her death she has been used as a symbol of French resistance.

00:23:14.411 --> 00:23:18.711
During both world wars she was called upon as a source of inspiration,

00:23:19.211 --> 00:23:24.251
perhaps not divine inspiration,  but she was used as an example of

00:23:24.251 --> 00:23:28.461
the French fighting spirit and bravery in the face of adversity.

00:23:29.981 --> 00:23:35.621
Despite this status as the so-called “maid of France”, a French icon who was

00:23:35.621 --> 00:23:40.841
decisively anti-English, there are a few important points to be made that go

00:23:40.871 --> 00:23:45.101
somewhat against this narrative, and I’m not only saying this as an Englishman.

00:23:46.361 --> 00:23:52.621
Firstly, she was put on trial by the English, but of the 131 members

00:23:52.621 --> 00:23:56.326
of the church who were involved in her trial, and who found her

00:23:56.341 --> 00:24:02.725
guilty, 123 were French, she was found guilty and killed by the French.

00:24:04.005 --> 00:24:08.395
Secondly, she was caught not by the English but by the Bugundians,

00:24:08.395 --> 00:24:12.735
supporters of the Duke of Burgundy, and as anyone who likes their red

00:24:12.735 --> 00:24:17.445
