Now, as for Joan herself, as you might imagine, modern historians and medical professionals have

00:25:00.782 --> 00:25:06.642
tried to rationally explain her condition and her visions, if indeed they were not the word of God.

00:25:07.652 --> 00:25:13.602
There’s a theory she might have been schizophrenic, epileptic, or even have had a lump in her brain.

00:25:14.902 --> 00:25:18.102
Whether or not these are true is anyone's guess.

00:25:18.932 --> 00:25:24.612
What seems to be hard to deny is that she really believed that she had been visited by

00:25:24.612 --> 00:25:30.133
messengers of God, that she was divinely appointed to save France, that she had been chosen.

00:25:31.023 --> 00:25:35.753
She believed she was exactly who she said she was; she was no fraud.

00:25:36.933 --> 00:25:42.103
During her four and a half month trial against a group of 131 learned clergymen

00:25:42.633 --> 00:25:47.613
she was able to hold her own, staying steadfast in her own convictions.

00:25:48.543 --> 00:25:53.783
She didn’t give up, she faced her fate with pride, even asking an

00:25:53.813 --> 00:25:58.153
English soldier to allow her to see the cross as she burned to death.

00:25:59.533 --> 00:26:04.013
Whether you believe or not that she was truly the saviour of France is

00:26:04.023 --> 00:26:09.983
